The Prague Stock Exchange ended with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall of the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
<0xC4><0x8C>EZ’s stock trades reached about half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of trading Tuesday, reacted immediately to Monday’s fall when it fell to about 6 percent.
The fall this time is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
Also here is the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American Assembly of Representatives who refused to support the stabilization plan of the secretary of the financial sector.
Falling shares in Asia
Asian stocks fell sharply on Tuesday, though the index eventually mitigated some of the losses throughout the day.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Stock Exchange index over its financial day stood at nearly four percent, although it later mitigated its losses by reducing the decline by nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index that tracks Chinese stock movements on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell 3.8 percent, with Shanghai markets closed.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the Index secretary, fell to 3.6 percent.
“The planned rescue actions in the U.S. are unsafe and this influences the financial markets around the world,” said the head of the Hong Kong Mint, Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, that is, without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong’s interest rates are at the same level as those of the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should meet again as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that the drops will be felt in other countries.
The Bloody Bath of American Stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the $700 billion (almost 12 trillion crowns) plan to help the financial system.
Lawmakers, in that way, ignored President George Bush’s invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks experienced a bloody bath and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell to nearly seven percent. A similar volume drop was last recorded in 1987.
The index fell before it was announced but as soon as it was shown that the assembly’s proposal did not go forward, the index began to fall freely.
Congress Withdraws: U.S. Government May Inject $700 Billion Into Banking
The highest representatives of Congress and the government, President George W. Bush, agreed on a pact in broad terms of financial aid to the American financial system.
Its vote will take place early next week.
U.S. lawmakers sparked a rift in talks about approving the bailout in the form of aid to the U.S. financial system in the amount of $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion crowns).
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must fine-tune some details of the contract before they can make the final form of the law public and vote on it.
The plan to help the financial system will be discussed Monday in the Assembly of Representatives.
He told Reuters on Sunday, Barney Frank, chairman of the Committee for Financial Services and Assembly Banking.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could be held in the Senate no earlier than Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the bailout plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
Afterwards, however, "disenchantment" will be achieved thanks to the complex mechanisms whose market aid will also reach in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made a great breakthrough.
We resolved our disagreeing views regarding the form that the package of measures for market stabilization should take," Democrat Nancy Pelosia told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still be held on Sunday.
Representatives from lawmakers met Sunday night with Finance Minister Henry Paulson to give a definitive form to the government fund.
It should buy from financial corporations the unsold mortgage assets that lead financial firms to heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are about to close the agreement on the plan, which will work and must also be effective in the market.
It’s still necessary to continue with the sanitation plan, but I think we’re already on it,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian businesses
The global financial crisis is expressly affecting the rapidly falling stock market.
According to Nevada Sen. Harry Reid, lawmakers are doing everything they can to get Congress to finally pass a deal on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors’ businesses in the face of the Asian finance market since these are the ones that are in the first time zone and where Congress could influence Monday’s trade.
However, for now there is nothing clear about when the two chambers of Congress will vote and, even if they will not stall at the last moment with some problem.
Lawmakers believe it will be passed in the coming days.
The law, however, will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system should be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion must be made available as soon as possible, as requested by President George Bush.
However, Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, which would be another $100 billion and, later, the last $350 billion.
Bush appreciated the progress of the meetings
On the other hand, the president can veto this decision but Congress can overcome its veto by a majority of votes.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program was retained, which consisted of earning financial resources for the repurchase of bad mortgage securities whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to finish paying off their mortgages.
“We have worked everything.
The House of Representatives would have to be prepared to vote on the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Sen. Judd Gregg.
U.S. President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the meetings.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush is pleased with Saturday’s advance and that he values “the commitment of both sides to stabilize our financial market and protect our economy.”
Limitation of armored contract
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, head of the negotiators, said lawmakers had decided on the liability of the program’s money to protect taxpayers’ taxes from their losses, an alleviating closure of the planned finance plan.
The new law should also limit so-called armored contracts for directors of the companies participating in the program, and create a committee that will have control of the Fund.
This would have to be directed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on it, and we’ve made a big step toward the agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes helping homeowners who have problems with their payments.
The government would have to agree to the new mortgage payments it buys in order to lower the monthly burdens of debtors’ installment payments and enable them to stay with their homes.
Marek: psychological help
The proposed plan is, according to Patria Finance’s chief economist, David Marek, a good idea that will be realized but rather difficult.
“And that’s why it’s not known by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be purchased.
This will be decisive for the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week, for the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not, according to Marek, as relevant.
"Much more important is that, already this week, congressmen agree on his support and give him their approval as soon as possible.
This important and psychological agreement to get that approval is, at the moment, the most important thing," Marek insisted.
Armed Fighting: The MP3 Player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
Which seems clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Yet there are sufficient reasons for man to acquire only the reproductor.
The choice depends practically on the way of its use and the demand of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for you to acquire the most modern record player to listen to in it the latest album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the other hand, this type of musical products such as LP records no longer come out, and as far as their quality is concerned, there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If vinyl records with art rock, jazz or blues music are crowded on your shelves, you are probably dreaming at least of this type of turntable.
This is the same with music that is on its way, that is, compressed, simplified music - music in MP3.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try the helmets of a market of twenty crowns.
Two ends, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also decides the battery life
Some of the best players achieve much more than just playing music and even what not even most mobile phones.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
In front of the most elementary functions such as telephone, send messages, can play music and video, record both, has a better or worse camera and can even get to navigate.
And when we take into account the Smartphone and the PDAs will have in their pocket also a small computer.
This is a small miracle since no refrigerator knows how to make a barbecue and no television can photograph.
The universality of mobiles also brings us disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile the sooner the display indicator will light up asking to be recharged.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy swallows.
There are few mobile phones that can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most of them much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) clearly have higher performance.
Therefore, keep in mind that cheap mobile phones will not play for more than two hours.
If in addition to this, on top of it, constantly call still get, for more safety, a charger for work - this is also true for the most expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player this problem will not have, because even the worst endure at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem happens when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately only a part of the devices has the universal USB connector and, moreover, not all of them can connect directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, it is possible to record music directly on the memory card but only on some readers without reduction can be connected the small memory cards that are used on mobiles.
In players, with some exception (iPod), no special software is required.
Just fill the device with music via the USB of the computer.
Most mobiles and players create their own order in the music library based on the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
For the choice of a specific equipment, be interested in the resistance of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and the type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of its operation.
If you listen, above all, to music in the background and listen to it every day just for a while, like on the tram, then any mobile you play is enough.
This is something that virtually any mobile phone can achieve.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or player plays the music.
The MP3 is played by everyone and practically all the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it the absolute majority of devices play music in WMA format.
The minus ones include the AAC format (format used by the Apple company and your iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough to visit the relevant pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album through the mobile internet.
This service could by itself be a weighty argument for acquiring a mobile for music.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is miserable and most are limited only to the fleeting success themes of the radios.
The prices are also not the lowest.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (whether by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a mobile phone.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you will find the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or, at least, handsfree.
If not, you can use a built-in player that has virtually every mobile even if it’s at least one MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobiles with music will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can already acquire a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the lack of an input for classic headphones.
The best, even when it comes to the technical part, such as phones equipped with a 3.5 mm input. for classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing but their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are really handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, its handling similar to the previous current cassettes or also to the turntables is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with the mobile and, consequently, gigantic account for data download.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (for example, the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot to change the memory card (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card you will reach two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
The basic models are usually equipped only with a 2 GB maximum capacity card.
Only the most expensive ones have a memory of 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) it is not necessary to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you consider yourself one of the most demanding music lovers, take advantage of the most specialized walkman-mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of the same player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose phones of the walkman line have almost identical use as that of a standalone MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, over four thousand crowns, but with a greater capacity of memory (up to 16 GB) and accumulator (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand cited more arria brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to be long.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunication Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole of the Union.
After the European Commission’s latest steps in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to emerge – for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
In contrast, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, has already stated that there is no longer a place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a marked decrease in prices to which the classical operators had to react also.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only half a year, this operator managed to get more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group that, besides that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual traders is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large expenses in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world these types of virtual operators are usually outlined with low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, are often countered with the offer of tighter services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half cheap compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a trivial goal group.
This operator specifically targets man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and who he can trust,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works for this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept like that of Poland could hook up in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told mobile.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not lean towards this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to advance the meetings," said the group's spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times flash.
It seems that, according to unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, a spokesman for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators are concerned with the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional conformity with O2’s opinion, adds: “To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop.”
He adds: “On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that it would be possible to study in such a short horizon."
Vodafone focuses on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of sharing costs and infrastructure.
Precisely we consider it as the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a drop in prices and with it, a decrease in profits.
So why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the company T-Mobile.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the websites of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: “Moreover, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
As regards the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail for him and, above all, for his services large requirements."
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Bids (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, she expressed her typical stance on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was closed.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer from potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for classical operators," added Kristian Chalupa, from the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS Department of Foreign Affairs, to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers this is more than a consideration, apart from that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the lower prices of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market means and the fall in prices do not fall within the interest of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really the dramatic shock in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, offers itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
“The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have a corresponding rise of responsibility in their actions in the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as are telecommunication regulators,” Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of conflict.
Obviously there is a relevant market analysis prepared by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary the agreement with the administrator of the network.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are strikingly similarly up.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators there are many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We have met with him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law for the extension of the competence of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of commercial tenders was recently introduced, which was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this perfectly well, but it is clear that their interests lie elsewhere.
All is well, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator still operates unnoticed, a few of which already exist in Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that engage in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases like the ones you cite were discovered, it could be a breach of the terms of the contract that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová replied to the question about this problem.
But it’s quite unlikely that such activity by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make nothing negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it at all as a normal customer of the carriers."
Precisely this is what should seem to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators turn their eyes on this type of procedure, why are they blocking the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we cease to be the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, at this time the regulatory bodies have intervened and in none of the cases have they defended the operators but their customers.
Whether it was with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to create the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge others.
Sadly, the Czech Regulatory Body is passing through this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But we don't despair.
If this information behind the scenes is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile market is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators lets in a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we will perhaps stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
