The MHD in Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the history of the Prague Transport Company writes the date on which the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased at this time by almost one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from January 1, 2009) and simultaneously charge it on their chip card at the infocentres and transport company stalls at the Metro stations, Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE>í Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>kál, Roztyly, Kot<0xC5><0x88>any, Raj, Kazty<0xC4><0x8D>, and Let<0xC5><0x88>any.
The bonds can be purchased from yesterday online on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce, can definitely start to forget about the ticket stalls in the subway stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is a window available to passengers with trained staff that helps those interested with the purchase online and also with the recharge of the voucher purchased on their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>.
