Rats also have feelings.
It is said that a rat or a cockroach feeling the danger flees, why is it also afraid?
Joseph Le Doux, the scientist in the field of neurology is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
How can we control whether they, behaving in the same way as us, feel the same way?
In an internet magazine called "Edge" for many years are published the contributions of famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series the answers chosen to the question What do you think is true without being able to prove it?
I think animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now, although we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case at least we can expect it because all human brains have the same fundamental configuration.
But as soon as we dedicate ourselves to other species and include the questions about sensation and in general about consciousness, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as the other animals: it makes the dead, runs away or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists make conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
Of course I don't believe it.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to infect our subjective experience to that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated by human consciousness with the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (because of their involvement in short memory and conduct-directing executive functions).
