Talking in sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up very smart telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens, you may be scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder that is called sleep apnea.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (sleeping) or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be so.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitement.
It is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him exit in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the sleep talks appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful Tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Although he is speaking, he is sleeping and therefore is resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes it would be advisable to consult or find out what is what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common), do not be tempted to question him to get information from him.
You will achieve nothing, because when you are asleep you are not conscious enough to organize your thinking.
Also you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even a joke.
This creates children's anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing bad, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
