The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Above all, it regained the public’s confidence that it had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated with the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not occur again.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, nearly 38 percent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, remembers Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained the public’s confidence,” he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94 percent of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "confidence is extremely fragile."
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we institute measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleid acid tests that allow the direct detection in the blood of donors of the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until now were based.
Nucleid acid tests allowed shortening the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk of certain donors being infected unknowingly and not being detected.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contained blood.
“That means you’ll have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that you can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain health without worries," says the head of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We have to be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary says, before underlining that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Since the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which on average brings together only 3 per cent of eligible Quebecers for blood donation. "
All healthy 18-year-olds who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travelled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But members of this network of donors must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and incite them to be a regular donor.
Since current life is very rampant, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood,” says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample and we expect to take more than a thousand of these out per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood taking program as very popular.
“Many moms are disappointed that they can’t enjoy this,” as Héma-Québec doesn’t have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in every hospital in Quebec.
