Free Opinion - The Orwellian Discourse of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world’s largest gold company tried a six-million-euro defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to spark a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his own?
The result of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will muzzle the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is before public opinion that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in a number of countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually about change of mind and not at clubbing.
It was enough for the miner to open her books, her files and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the financing of independent search teams that would have been able to clarify the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to distrust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can call for a "public" debate by scorning his views?
According to the Vice-President, it seems that this word designates only high-paying lawyers and not for all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects the mining’s brutal manner.
This public is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but on the basis of civilized changes of arguments, and not in the framework of what many people perceive as a chase-gag (persecuting the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a request regarding the authors of Noir Canada intiming them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold trial is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and make a debate about the facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under pain of many persecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate prosecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he claims, he does not want to make a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
Wall Street bailout operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan that aims to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms aimed at ensuring the reimbursement of public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for lack of payment, as well as a right of control over the wages paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Sen. Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We are making great progress towards a deal that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done to cover up the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“It’s the bottom line: If we don’t do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect of a new failure in the mood of investors.
The last time they had set themselves was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the U.S. presidential election, who have acceded late to the negotiations, were rather favorable to the agreement, without however forgetting to express their discontent of being forced to reach this extremity.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the deal, particularly one that would allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of the executives of the surviving companies by the state.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, we should not congratulate ourselves.
But these measures are necessary,” he said on American television.
His Republican adversary, John McCain, asked on another network whether he would vote for the proposed plan, responded that: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it."
"The important points I read [show] that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said the option of doing nothing is not acceptable.”
The $700 billion plan aims to buy the dubious debts, risky assets and invendibles of American financial institutions with taxpayer money.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans before spreading to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and causing a liquidity freeze and a slump of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe we have come out of stalemate since Democrats accepted that certain “toxic” assets of companies in distress are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In an effort to smooth out the rough patches for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that stipulated that if the government had to take on losses for five years under this program, it could impose new taxes that would aim to help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of $250 billion to which another $100 billion can be added if the president sees fit.
The payment of another $350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote on the part of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will earn dividends in the event of profits and that it can re-sell when the storm is past.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying the embargo procedures concerning homes obtained with real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on the remuneration and on the cash compensation paid to the managers of the companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote of the House of Representatives from today and to that of the Senate next Wednesday.
Despite all your efforts, you are still not sure if your plan will be approved.
Some people continued to protest against the bill yesterday, both Republicans and Democrats alike.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents that "clearly, Washington doesn't want to understand."
"We have a very serious financial problem.
There are solutions.
But not the one that consists of profiting from taxpayers.”
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, who is a small group cheerleader in Congress, presents the issues differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us to tell us: We ask Congress not to hurry and to carefully examine the way forward,” he said.
At this very moment, in Europe, we again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
Following an urgent meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of Fortis banking group for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up buying its bankrupt competitor since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) during the risky real estate lending crisis in the United States.
