Psychology of overlaps: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological—economic—basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this “game” through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was playing the lottery, the other was participating in an auction and in the meantime the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-premiering" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to the scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To support their theory, the economists of the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more in prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winning" group.
"These results cannot be inferred from any previously existing economic theory.
For until now, they explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University’s School of Economics.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
About 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses in dependence on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: Hepatitis A and E via food (for example with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humors (sperm, vagina mood, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves by vaccine against viruses A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear on the skin and on the whites of the eyes jaundice, excrement becomes clear, dark colored urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die worldwide of liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature recognition, systematic medical monitoring, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory monitoring as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has cure if discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
It aims to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less for those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent research, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed religious belief in how it influences human pain, the British newspaper The Telegraph reported.
As part of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of investigations in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University participate alongside academics.
The analysis occurred as follows; they attached a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants in the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the work of Sassoferrato of the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci’s Lady of the Arminium of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious encouragement among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
The patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving in that period 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt “safe” as “protected” people, “they were reassured and peace reigned in their hearts.”
