You are what you say about yourself
On his tenth birthday, Google can say: he can be found both in people’s pockets, and in the sky above their heads; he knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what it is that interests them.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who make a parallel with the Orwellian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to gather as much personal data about its users as possible, and this is necessary to be able to meet the original goals of the founders of Google: “We gather in one system all the information in the world!”
According to the leader of Google, the company even after ten years of work that stirred the world is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to process all the information.
To the question what is going to happen in five years, Schmidt replied: I would like Google to be able to answer questions such as “What to do tomorrow?” or “What would be the job that best suits me?” – however, the software won’t be able to answer questions that seemingly simple until there is enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their browsing on the Internet the searched keywords, IP addresses and the pages where they passed at the end of the search are accurately stored.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can re-consult what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - on this same logic will be based the Recommendations, on which the system will offer products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What will happen if they take advantage of my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who worry about seeing the information monopoly of Google.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, longing for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a fact already confirmed that they not only preserve, but in justifiable cases also cede to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most debated example of recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google handed over to the Brazilian government the information on its website, called Orkut, to identify the pedophiles.
On the other hand, Internet users who care about people’s rights were relieved in May when the company together with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully demonstrated before the court that it was right in its litigation with the FBI: according to the sentence, Google will not be able to be forced, through any of the points of the constitution to provide any type of information requested in secret by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government managed to get under the pretext of enforcing the child protection law passed years ago, about 50,000 Web addresses and about 1,000 search phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of Web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
This is quite contradictory opinion about Google: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that it harms their privacy, their privacy by starting to use the services of Google, and rebel against it as against the multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not its rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the World, no matter how much they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for its applications, the code is open and the free program package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborating than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks accurately see the very problematic relationship between people’s rights and the Internet that was produced by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about leaving intentional footprints behind and taking advantage of the available communication channels, and while the measures of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then these can be included in a tracking system such as the FriendFeed or the Blip.fm, you can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are automatically stored on the F.
We can know numerous cases from which it follows that, for example, the bride, seeing the flow of photographs the next morning of common friends, learns who her fraudulent boyfriend spent the night before or they can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion in his blog about the management of the company: one thing is certain, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
A person’s online life is what she shows herself – this is the definition behind the behavior of today’s youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least tries to dodge Google’s monopoly, can do so (starting with the Scroogle that uses Google’s search system, but leaves no trace).
There are many people who do not want to register on the collective pages to prevent them from being found, but you can replace Google's "online" applications, from text writing software to image and news reading applications with alternative versions which do not connect with gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
The public is almost openly waiting for the day when Google will show its true face.
The company with its current value of 156 billion dollars is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), the advertising surfaces of AdWords / AdSense threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, while the numerous services that are introduced more and more quickly cause serious headaches not only to Microsoft but also to other companies.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example, the top management resolutely rejected the protest of the employees after doubling the price of the company's childcare, considered too expensive the unlimited number of employees feeding, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 the regime gave in to the moral interests of the Chinese government and the company according to the agreement violated all the good information.
One of the company’s internal regulations says they won’t announce any new services in advance, but only when it’s ready to work, what if certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years may turn the world upside down: while some believe that Google’s project of scanning and archiving books and magazines will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be cited by the U.S. health care Supreme Court, we can create our own system.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will be able to provide a good raw material for the writers of science fiction works, the Scroogled, novel of the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwelian form that future, in which a man only of the data of Google can be described alarmingly well.
