Smart Car Imitates Bumblebee Flight
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of obstacles sensors existing in nature?
For example, the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic steering system of cars type BR23C imitator of nature, to which they gave the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule – explained at the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, chief technology officer for PR and development and research.
The compound eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of compound eyes, the engineers used the laser length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at a 180-degree angle, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle’s microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot mimicking the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If this were not the case, the vehicle robot would not be able to react quickly enough to dodge obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which currently all types of collisions are considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in an open and close eyes.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotational movement and the acceleration in addition to the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the processing capacity of the data, much less the storage capacity.
This apparatus every second only needs to process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte or megabyte memory is needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge obstacles, which, according to Nissan’s calculations, can be incorporated into mass-produced models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, dodging obstacles existing in his way.
