Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008 domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices, the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent from July 2008 and fell 3.9 percent from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose only to a minimal extent, at 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry rose slightly, at 0.1 percent from July.
The largest increase in price magnitude occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to a 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastics and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in chemicals production branch prices (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 percent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the other sectors of the processing industry, there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was recorded in August, firstly as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period – in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors – the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector there was an increase of 13.2 percent, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5%), as well as in the manufacture of electric machines and instruments (0.3%).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Electricity, gas, heat and water prices were 18.7 percent higher than last year’s prices.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3 percent, in the energy sector and in the intermediate sectors there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods industries, there was a decrease of 6.8 percent and in investment goods, a decrease of 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased 1.1 percent from the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
