MP3 Players Under Accusation, Put Hearing at Risk
Listening to music at high volume for a long period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing injury.
The European Commission, in a statement released in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Commission on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risk (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day having the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
“I am concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at an elevated acoustic level can unconsciously ruin their ears in an irremediable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“From the scientific evidence, a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What counts is to sensitize consumers and make this information public.
We must also re-examine the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are widely effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the large use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that this causes.
The scientists confirm that this is a cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could eventually be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music and related devices.
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB, but concern increases as hearing damage may result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing noise levels and exposure time.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices listen to loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the limit currently in force regarding the maximum noise allowed at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
It means that it affects 5-10% of users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
