Scientists have been inspired by gecko paws, coated with microscopic hairs that can ensure the animal a perfect adhesion.
Tests done on different materials, such as glass, teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of this reptile and at the same time “easily peels off the walls,” explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton School of Engineering.
“This material could be useful as a transient adhesive,” Liming Dai adds.
Layers to walk on walls exactly like Spider-Man? Layers yes, but researchers think of a far less fascinating use as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
