Kohl, 26, is the fourth positive third-generation EPO racer, after Italians Riccardo Ricc<0xC3><0xB2> and Leonardo Piepoli and German Stefan Schumacher, also from Gerolsteiner.
Tests of Kohl's blood samples are among those carried out in recent weeks in the laboratory in Lausanne and Chatenay-Malabry.
If the tests confirm that he is positive, the Austrian will lose third place in the Tour and anger against the two years of canonical disqualification.
Confirming the news of the positive doping of Kohl to the third generation EPO is the head of the French anti-doping agency, Pierre Bordry, who has told the Associated Press that he notified the Austrian authorities of the news.
The 26-year-old Austrian has placed on the podium behind the Spanish Carlos Sastre and the American Cadel Evans, winning the t-shirt of the best climber.
IMMIGRANTS:NEW YORK TIMES QUESTIONS, IS ITALY RACISTIC?
Italy, a country of emigrants, has only recently become a privileged destination for immigrants "welcomed with hostility.
Is this transforming the beautiful country into a nation of racists? This is what the New York Times asks in a long article that has devoted to the debate on the issue of racism in Italy starting from the case of the young Abdul William Guibre from Burkina Faso murdered the previous month in Milan for stealing a box of cookies.
This case underscores what the New York Times calls the “northern paradox”: the northern regions are at the same time those where there is “more integration and more work” but also the highest anti-immigrant sentiment in the country and the highest support of the Northern League.
As confirmed by the growing tension between Italians and immigrants, the New York Times has also cited the episodes of intolerance in Milan, Parma, Rome, Ciampino and Castel Volturno.
Not alone.
Also the new legislation wanted by the League tightens the brakes on immigration and facilitates the expulsion of illegal immigrants is cited as a paradigm of climate change in Italy.
A trend marked by both the Pope and the President of the Republic: "Giorgio Napolitano meeting Benedict XVI in Congress has asked the State and the Church to work together to combat racism."
Students victims of expensive rent, up to 900 euros for a room
The rent market for college students does not know the crisis.
According to the latest Sunia survey, the tenants’ union, renting a single room could cost a student 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"the phenomenon has already assumed very serious characteristics to the point of excluding the right to study a large part of young people for the very high costs that the family would have to support - explains the head of the studies office of the Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities the strong demand has totally distorted the market to the point of triggering a process of widespread increase even for the residents".
Apart from that in most cases the rental offers contain a series of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, without limit of fee, sub rentals linked.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions are necessary that, through the revision of the taxation, prices can be regulated.
Looking at the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, they serve approximately 450 euros; for a single room from a minimum of 650 (Bande Nere area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (Victoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas near the University, they serve 250/280 euros for a bed in a double room and 370 to 500 for a single one.
In Rome in the central areas near the University (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) they ask about 600 euros for a single room and 450 for a bed in a double room.
Only slightly lower values (550 euros for a single room) in areas near other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
It saves only if you change peripheral area: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room in Prenestina area, Centocelle and surroundings.
In Naples for a bed you are served 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Polyclinic, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for a bed you are served 250/350 euro, at least 350 for an individual.
in smaller cities the prices are lower in absolute terms, but has a greater weight in the economy of the city.
In cities such as Perugia, where the phenomenon of rents to students and non-EU citizens is more frequent, there is a further anomaly: a 25/30% increase in the fee for foreign students compared to Italians.
Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic halls
Historical cinemas close favoring multiplexes.
“A city without movie theaters in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the big Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the big meticones in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono halls in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
Disappearing are almost always historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the Oscar cousin and the grand prize of the jury at Cannes, which told the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for the way of living always lost cinema.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of merchants, speak for themselves: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and most of them are paid for by the halls of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas less, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these three Italian regions are the ones that have registered the greatest number of new meticone cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, “it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its attendees are willing to transfer to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is disgraceful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros per year.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that worried about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono sala both in the historic center and in the periphery.
Among the rules foreseen are tax facilitation measures in favour of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic area and will have special fees for parking.
“It is an initiative that I like”, observes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of meticones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me was always important: the closure of the cinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "Nuevo cine Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
Link between politics and 'ndrangheta, the mayor of Gioia Tauro has been arrested
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was available to uniformize the elections of the Municipality for those interested to the Piromalli Cossa."
The charges are heavy that the magistrates of the Anti-Mafia Directorate of Calabria give to the mayor and deputy mayor of Goia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for mafia association.
He was also arrested Gioacchino Piromalli, the old mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his grandson, a lawyer of the same name for the boss, already convicted of mafia criminal association and to compensate 10 million euros.
"Disregarding any legal and moral norms, and good sense," the prosecutors write, the two local administrations had expressed a willingness to pay consultations to lawyer Piromalli.
“The mafia family would have been allowed to officially enter the municipality, facilitating the great possibility of control and command of the public administration.”
The president of the Calabrian regional board Agazio Loiero does not hide that "agreements between the bad organized life there are a lot" in his region: "There are areas where the mafia intensity is stronger than in others, where the agreement is almost inevitable.
But there are so many local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'ndrangheta, heroes who stay clean."
The arrests this morning add to those last July after police had announced the head-cutting of the Piromalli mafia family.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, already in 1991 and always due to alleged conditioning between organized crime and the local administration, the local politicians had been relieved of the task of administering the municipality.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, mayor of the UDC at the time of the dissolution, after the ballot in May 2006, had been elected as head of a center-right coalition.
I exploded a scandal when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
I call into question the vice minister of the interior who at that time was Marco Minniti, accusing him of having organized everything for a political issue, but the judges in the arrest warrant signed this morning explain that Piromalli had even asked for the variation of the A3 road project.
From the environmental intercepts made at Dal Torrione, the judges write, emerges "the willingness to favor the demands of an entrepreneur, representative of a group very close to the Piromalli clan, uniformizing the elections of the public administration over the interests of the mafia families".
When the energy is born from the waves, the great ones come down to the stage.
It is an exterminated deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the big ones like Chevron look.
The possibility of collecting energy from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s along with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was pushed aside, but now that environmental cases and the new increase in oil give momentum to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated by 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of sea waves.
This amount would be double that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has sealed an agreement to build an implant in the North of Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy are always more and among these companies that have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technology,” a spokesperson for a company associated with the U.S. oil colossus told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It is a pretty important sign, considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to carry out new drilling.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, even if not detailed indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, because marine energy has no doubt a great environmental impact.
For now impacts like those of the Portuguese or the Scots are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas joined together.
The force of the waves, which makes the boa move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure rotates a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast through submarine cables.
For now there are four implants of this type in development, awaiting only federal approval, apart from energy, could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and for a parking lot, using submarine turbines on the East River in New York.
The movement of water when there are tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said it has a long roster of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the power.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say in the Institute for the Development of Electricity, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is mainly about tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others approaching the coast, have invested $7.5 million in 2008 and an investment of $35 million is planned for 2009.
